{{Infobox religious building| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |name= Rokkō Hime Daizen Shrine | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |image= [[File:Rokkohime shrine, Kobe.jpg|280px|Rokkō Hime Daizen Shrine, Oku-no-in of Taimon-ji Temple]] |location= {{ill|Nada-ku, Kobe|ja|灘区|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|ja|兵庫県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Rokkōzan Town|ja|六甲山町|12=draft|12=draft}} |Latitude = 34 | Latitude_min = 45 | Latitude_sec = 58.72 |Longitude = 135 | Longitude_min = 14 | Longitude_sec = 21.91 |Map= Kobe#Japan Hyogo |deity= Rokkō Hime Daizen God ({{ill|Saeōrihime|ja|瀬織津姫|1=Seoritsu-Hime|12=draft|12=draft}}) |Sacred_object= {{ill|Iwakura|ja|磐座|12=draft|12=draft}} (sacred rock) |Rank= |consecration_year= |Main_hall= |Other_names= |Special_associations= |Festival= |Rituals= }}
'''Rokkō Hime Daizen Shrine''' (六甲比命大善神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Nada-ku, Kobe|ja|灘区|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|ja|兵庫県|12=draft|12=draft}}, known for its sacred {{ill|iwakura rock|ja|磐座|12=draft|12=draft}} (rock formation) as the object of worship.
Situated near the ridgeline of {{ill|Mount Rokkō|ja|六甲山|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine is close to other sacred sites such as the rock formation dedicated to {{ill|Ame-no-Hohi|ja|天穂日命|12=draft|12=draft}} within the Rokkō Country House grounds.
== deity == * Main deity - Rokkō Hime Daizen God (identified as {{ill|Benzaiten|ja|弁財天|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kichijōten|ja|吉祥天|12=draft|12=draft}}), also known as Tsukisakaki Itsu-no-Mitama Amasakaru Mukatsu Hime (撞賢木厳魂天疎向津姫, {{ill|Saeōrihime|ja|瀬織津姫|1=Seoritsu-Hime|12=draft|12=draft}}).
The deity’s name has evolved along with the mountain’s name, reflecting its role as a water god influencing the region’s renowned springs such as {{ill|Arima Onsen|ja|有馬温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nunobiki Waterfall|ja|布引の滝|12=draft|12=draft}}, and the renowned {{ill|Miya Water|ja|宮水|12=draft|12=draft}} used in brewing by the Nada Gōgō.
== History == The shrine’s sacred rock formation is believed to be a man-made structure from the {{ill|Jōmon period|ja|縄文時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, possibly constructed around 5,000 BCE. It was used by early Jōmon people for religious practices.
According to legend, the shrine was once the {{ill|Okunomiya|ja|奥宮|12=draft|12=draft}} (inner shrine) of {{ill|Hirota Shrine|ja|廣田神社|12=draft|12=draft}} and was also associated with the {{ill|Ara-matsuri-no-miya|ja|荒祭宮|12=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}.
The current sacred site is managed collaboratively by {{ill|Taimon-ji Temple|ja|多聞寺 (神戸市北区)|12=draft|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Rokkō Hime Society|ja|六甲比命講|12=draft|12=draft}}, with rituals such as autumn goma fire ceremonies conducted jointly.
== Recent Developments == In recent years, the shrine has gained popularity as a {{ill|power spot|ja|パワースポット|12=draft|12=draft}}. Various groups now hold events near the sacred rocks, and visitors can obtain shrine-related materials, such as {{ill|goshuin|ja|御朱印|12=draft|12=draft}}, talismans, and photos of sacred imagery.
== Access == === By Car === From {{ill|Takarazuka|ja|宝塚|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nishinomiya|ja|西宮|12=draft|12=draft}}, or {{ill|Kobe|ja|神戸|12=draft|12=draft}} via Hyōgo Prefectural Route 16, head toward {{ill|Rokkō Athletic Park GREENIA|ja|六甲山アスレチックパークGREENIA|12=draft|12=draft}}. Parking is available near the shrine, with additional paid parking at GREENIA.
=== By Public Transportation === From {{ill|JR Shin-Kobe Station|ja|新神戸駅|12=draft|12=draft}}, take the subway to {{ill|Sannomiya|ja|三宮|12=draft|12=draft}}. Transfer to JR or Hankyū lines to reach {{ill|Rokkō Station|ja|六甲駅|12=draft|12=draft}}. From there, take the bus to Rokkō Cable Car Station, ascend to Rokkōzan Station, and proceed to the shrine.
